At the moment shoppers can pay for items worth up to £20 simply by touching it against a reader, rather than entering their PIN or signing anything.

There are now 58million contactless cards in circulation in the UK and they are accepted by many major chains and organisations including Aldi, Boots, Waitrose and even Barnardo's.

Transport for London launched contactless payments across the transport network in the capital last September.

Shashi Verma, Transport for London's director of customer experience, said: 'We have seen over 41 million journeys made across London using contactless within just five months.

'Using contactless payments to travel can save our customers time, they don't need to stop to top-up an Oyster card, or buy a ticket.'

People using contactless spend £8.26 per transaction, on average.

Separate figures revealed that Bristol has seen the most significant increase in contactless usage in 2014, when compared with the country's other major cities.

